{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}

'''Charl Jean Francois Cilliers''' (also credited as ''Charles Cilliers'') (born on 25 January 1941) is a [[South Africa]]n author and poet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.volksblad.com/Boeke/Nuus/The-Journey-kyk-nuut-na-geykte-sake-20100404|title=The Journey kyk nuut na geykte sake|last=Hambidge|first=Joan|date=4 April 2010|work=[[Volksblad]]|language=Afrikaans|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref> His published works include "West-falling Light" (1971), "Has Winter No Wisdom" (1979).

'''Early Years and Education'''
Cilliers was born in [[Cape Town]], and grew up in [[Free State (South African province)|Free State]]. His [[Primary education|primary school]] years were spent in a succession of different schools as the family moved around. He went to Clapham High School in [[Pretoria]], where he [[matriculation|matriculated]] in 1957. 

Cilliers lectured in telecommunications in the [[Post office|Post Office]] Training Centre in Pretoria until 1968 when he joined Parliament as a translator. He retired as Chief Editor of the Hansard Reporting Unit until in 1999.

His published volumes are:

West-Falling Light, Tafelberg Publishers, 1971;
Has Winter No Wisdom, Maskew Miller, 1979;
Collected Poems (1960 - 2008), Malgas Publishers, 2008;
Fireflies Facing The Moon (Children's Poems), Malgas Publishers, 2008;
The Journey, Malgas Publishers, 2010;
A Momentary Stay, Malgas Publishers, 2011;
Karoo (Haiku Variations), 2012.

==Writing==
Charl J. F. Cilliers writing poetry at the age of 14. His first volume "West-falling Light" was published in 1971, followed by "Has Winter No Wisdom" in 1979. He has  published in magazines such as Standpunte, Contrast, Ophir, Poet (India), Purple Renoster, New Nation (of which he was also poetry editor), De Arte,  Chirimo (Rhodesia) and Unisa [[English studies|English Studies]].

His work also appeared in anthologies such as "Two Roads" (compiled by Ken Durham in 1969), "Seismograph" (compiled by [[Jack Cope]] in 1970), "For All Seasons" (compiled by F. C. H. Rumboll and J. B. Gardener in 1973), "Out Of The African Ark" (edited by David and [[Guy Butler (poet)|Guy Butler]] in 1988), "25/25" (edited by David Bunyan in 1989) and "Somewhere I Have Never Travelled" (edited by Terrill Nicolay in 1996).

His poems have also been broadcast by the SABC.

== Published poetry ==
*West-Falling Light (1971)
*Has Winter No Wisdom (1979)
*Collected Poems (2008)
*Fireflies Facing The Moon (Children<U+2019>s Poems, 2008)
*Work In Progress
*The Journey
*World In A Grain Of Sand

